  "prompt": "What was the French New Wave?",
  "response": "The French New Wave (**Nouvelle Vague**) was a revolutionary film movement that emerged in France in the late 1950s and early 1960s. It fundamentally changed the way films were made and perceived, influencing cinema worldwide. Here are the key aspects of the movement:\n\n### **Origins and Context**\n1. **Post-War France**: The movement arose in the aftermath of World War II, as France was rebuilding and questioning traditional values and conventions.\n2. **Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma**: Many of the filmmakers associated with the New Wave were critics for the influential film magazine *Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma*. They rejected the conventional, studio-bound \"Tradition of Quality\" in French cinema and championed more personal, innovative, and experimental approaches.\n\n### **Key Filmmakers**\nThe movement included directors such as:\n- **Jean-Luc Godard** (*Breathless*, *Vivre Sa Vie*)\n- **Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut** (*The 400 Blows*, *Jules and Jim*)\n- **Claude Chabrol** (*Le Beau Serge*, *Les Cousins*)\n- **\u00c9ric Rohmer** (*My Night at Maud's*, *Claire's Knee*)\n- **Alain Resnais** (*Hiroshima Mon Amour*, *Last Year at Marienbad*)\n\n### **Characteristics of the French New Wave**\n1. **Auteur Theory**: Directors were seen as the \"authors\" of their films, with their personal style and vision taking precedence over studio control.\n2. **Narrative Experimentation**: Non-linear storytelling, ambiguous endings, and fragmented narratives were common.\n3. **Low-Budget Production**: Filmmakers often shot on location with handheld cameras, using natural lighting and improvised dialogue.\n4. **Breaking Conventions**: The New Wave rejected traditional cinematic rules, such as continuity editing, in favor of jump cuts, long takes, and self-referential elements.\n5. **Youth and Rebellion**: Films often focused on themes of alienation, freedom, and the struggles of young people, reflecting the social changes of the era.\n6. **Cultural References**: Films frequently referenced literature, philosophy, and other art forms, as well as paid homage to classic Hollywood and international cinema.\n\n### **Influence and Legacy**\nThe French New Wave had a profound impact on global cinema, inspiring movements such as:\n- The **New Hollywood** in the United States (e.g., Martin Scorsese, Francis Ford Coppola)\n- The **New German Cinema** (e.g., Rainer Werner Fassbinder, Werner Herzog)\n- **Independent Cinema** worldwide\n\nIts emphasis on creativity, personal expression, and technical innovation continues to influence filmmakers to this day.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
